Throughout landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the lost coast and now in the hands of Chile after a bloody 19th-century conflict over resources is still alive, as is the desire to cross the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes have perhaps reached their highest level in decades, as Bolivia awaits the decision of the International Court of Justice on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and obviously is waiting for the result with a positive attitude,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the ruling of the International Court of Justice on big screens across the country, in the hope that the Hague court will welcome Bolivia's claim that - after decades of intermittent dialogue - Chile is obliged to negotiate, guaranteeing Bolivia an outlet to the sea under the State's jurisdiction.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president — who is facing a controversial re-election battle next year — has much to do with Monday’s ruling.
“We are very close to our return to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court will hardly rule in favor of Bolivia and that little would change if it did.
The UN body based in the Netherlands has no power to allocate Chilean territory and has said it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the ruling of the International Court of Justice comes just six months after the final arguments indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from advancing the Bolivian cause, the past four years may have delayed it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been monopolized by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morale’s belligerent rhetoric has crushed any remaining good intentions of Chile, he suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at some point, but it will be very difficult to keep the discussions going after what happened.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
