John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish independent schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this continued into 2018 with another set of outstanding exam scores, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective endeavors.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare pupils for further higher education, their chosen careers and their place in the world as global citizens.
As an education sector capable of developing and adopting a customized school curriculum, we observe that modern languages continue to be a popular and in-demand subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message will reach his brain.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, the message will reach his heart.”
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone if we want to build trusting relationships with people from other countries.
From this year’s exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained the highest grades.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72% of students obtained the highest grade with honors in Chinese, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish obtained the highest grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as key skills for children and young people, who will undoubtedly need them in the future.
Currently, languages, as a choice of subject, are considered at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, technique and mathematics) in the curricula of independent institutes and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that the reasons employees indicated for the difficulty in filling jobs are attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
This is why language skills are becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of which career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have an effective advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will bring a multilingual person automatically ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language at a sufficient level to be able to maintain a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
This is why investing in language teaching is so important for children today.
Knowledge of several languages, particularly those in developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK looking to 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest is, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff specializing in this area.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the necessary skills for success, whatever their future.
There is no denying at this time, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
