North Korea Rejects Unilateral Disarmament Without Confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that maintaining the sanctions was deepening the country's distrust of the United States, which in such circumstances would absolutely refuse to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho said at the world body's General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“But we don’t see any compliant response from the US,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no security in our national security, and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
Although Ri re-used the well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization with which North Korea would be rewarded on the basis of gradual actions, his statement was important because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization altogether as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first-ever meeting between a US president in office and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work towards the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees of North Korean security.
North Korea sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease the tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The US insists on the need to "have denuclearization first" and to increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose in a coercive way and even opposes the "declaration of the end of the war," Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion of those who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our distrust.”
Ri did not refer to plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader announced at the U.N. earlier this week.
The minister pointed out the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: “If the counterpart to this issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be dead at this point.”
But even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was noticeably different from last year’s speech at the UN General Assembly, when he said it was inevitable to target U.S. territory with North Korea’s missiles after “evil president” Trump called Kim a “missile man” engaged in a suicide mission.
In front of the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in embarking on the path of disarmament, but said much more needed to be done and that sanctions will remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no deadline, stating that "whether it will take two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: “Compliance with Security Council sanctions must continue forcefully and without exception until complete, final and ascertained denuclearization is achieved.”
The Security Council unanimously endorsed sanctions against North Korea in 2006 in an attempt to stifle funding for nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again the following month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo visited North Korea already three times this year, but the last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea accused him of making “gangster requests.”
North Korea had pledged during a meeting this month with Moon to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States took “compliant measures.”
He said Kim had explained to him that the “compliant measures” he wanted were security guarantees to which Trump had committed in Singapore and actions towards a normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has pushed all its students to sleep more in an attempt to counter the growing manly culture of studying for whole nights fed by caffeine.
One university scholar found that students at the number one university in the world often have no idea of the basic concepts of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He had the idea to start the course after a lecture he had given on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, 'Why am I being told this only now, when I'm in senior year?'
She said no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me a lot,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students essential concepts of how good sleep-related habits can help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In one section there is the image of a dorm room, where students can select cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to be able to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know it won’t change students’ behavior immediately.
But we think they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,” Czeisler added.
The culture of pride tied to the “night in the blank to study” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to lack of sleep being an ever-growing problem.
Sleeping enough and with a good quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" to fight stress, fatigue, anxiety, he explained and should even serve to avoid gaining weight since the lack of sleep brings the brain into the mode of starvation, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student enrolled in the faculty of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course after taking one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduate students to follow a similar program of study before enrolling in this competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm clock for when they need to go to bed, as well as when they need to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can tilt the circadian rhythm, leading to sleeping problems.
