What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
This Saturday New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event that sees the performance of a remarkable cast of stars and has an equally remarkable mission: to end poverty in the world.
Now in its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will see tens of thousands of people pouring into the Great Lawn of Central Park not only to enjoy performances such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness about the real purpose of the event, to end extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international support group that hopes to eliminate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (unless they were willing to pay for a VIP ticket), the concert audience had to complete a number of tasks, or "actions" such as volunteering, emailing a world leader, making a phone call, or any other meaningful way that would help raise awareness about their goal of eradicating poverty.
But, precisely, how successful has the Global Citizen Festival been now that there are 12 years left to achieve its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really a genuine way to persuade people to call for a call to action, or is it just another example of so-called “clicktivism”—people who feel they really make a difference by simply signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen claims to have recorded more than 19 million “actions” from its supporters, working for a variety of different purposes.
It states that these actions have helped urge world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, destined to affect, by 2030, the lives of more than 2.25 billion people.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements arising from their actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been disbursed or used as funds.
The group estimates that protected capital funds have so far had a direct impact on approximately 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based investor-executor partnership committed to “helping children grow to their full potential,” with a pledge to provide Rwanda with $35 million to help eliminate malnutrition in the country, after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens just like you, we can make social injustice or malnutrition a footnote in history,” Tracey Ullman, The Power of Nutrition ambassador, told the crowd during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions calling on the UK to improve the nutrition of mothers and children, the government announced funding for a project, the Power of Nutrition, which will reach 5 million women and children through nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the FAQs on their website, which asked, “What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?”
Global Citizen responded: “It will be a long and arduous journey – sometimes we will fall and fail.
But, like the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will succeed, because together we are stronger.
