Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
Analyzing the recorded sounds by an expert will determine the frequency of bat calls and how each species behaves.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed scale picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes the results can reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating lawns, and how best to maintain forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
Bats are at risk due to construction and development work affecting trepoli and ruining habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can mosquitoicide paper and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to spot insects and obstacles on their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten skilled experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect drills and sometimes carry out rescues.
The organization even set up Scotland’s first bat-only reserve at the Threave estate in the Dumfries and Galloway region, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
