“Here at Threave we have a vast area for bats,” he said.
“We have the old buildings, many centuries-old trees and a good habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats yet, so the work we do here and on the other properties will help us understand more about their growth needs.”
It stresses the importance of checking bats before conducting maintenance within the properties as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternal trunk could kill up to 400 females and young, perhaps wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb, or destroy their stilts.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
