A strange statistic if you think that he is one of the greatest players of all time having won 14 of the main titles, second only to Jack Nicklaus.
The U.S. team has been trying all weekend to find the fairways, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played top-level golf throughout the tournament.
U.S. captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I’m proud of these guys because they fought.
At one point this morning we put pressure on the Europe team.
We threw away this opportunity.
Congratulations to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All his 12 players behaved very well.
We'll reorganize, I'll work with the American PGA and the Ryder Cup committee, and we'll move on.
I’m fond of these 12 guys and I’m proud to be their captain.
We've put all of it into it.
They played better than us.”
Red tide update: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentration in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy flowering conditions, suggesting a decrease in concentration, are evident in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties.
The red tide bloom extends for about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The patches are about 10 miles off Hillsborough County but in fewer areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
A low concentration in Pinellas County or off its coasts, a low to high concentration off Hillsborough County, a low concentration to a high concentration in Manatee County, a low concentration to a high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coasts, a low concentration to a high concentration in Charlotte County, a low concentration to a high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coasts, a low concentration to a high concentration in Charlotte County.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No cases were reported in Northwest Florida last week.
